    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Pteris pectiniformis improperly include inducing nausea due to its toxic saponins which can cause stomach upset and vomiting. Pteris pectiniformis may also cause nausea in some individuals due to its emetic properties, leading to discomfort and dehydration. Development of skin irritation is possible as the plant's saponins can cause skin inflammation and dermatitis. Improper use of Pteris pectiniformis can also lead to diarrhea as its saponins can irritate the digestive system and cause gastrointestinal issues. In rare cases, Pteris pectiniformis may trigger allergic reactions including anaphylaxis, which can be life-threatening and requires immediate medical attention.",
    "uses": "Pteris pectiniformis is a species of fern, and like many other ferns, it has been used in traditional medicine in various parts of the world. In some cultures, Pteris pectiniformis is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help to reduce swelling and pain. However, more research is needed to confirm the effectiveness of Pteris pectiniformis for medicinal purposes. The plant is often used in traditional remedies to treat various health issues, including fever, skin conditions, and digestive problems. Further studies are required to fully understand the potential health benefits of Pteris pectiniformis.",
    "taxonomy": "Pteris pectiniformis is a species of fern in the family Pteridaceae. It belongs to the genus Pteris, which consists of various species of bracken ferns. The Pteridaceae family is a group of ferns that are primarily epiphytic or terrestrial in habit. This classification is based on the plant's morphology, anatomy, and evolutionary relationships. The species is native to various parts of Asia, where it grows in shaded and humid environments.",
    "benefits": "Pteris pectiniformis is a type of fern known for its potential health benefits. It is traditionally used in some cultures to treat fever, rheumatism, and other inflammatory conditions. The plant's extracts may have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, which could contribute to its medicinal uses. Further research is needed to confirm its effectiveness in treating various health conditions. Some studies suggest that Pteris pectiniformis may also have antiviral and antibacterial properties.",
    "parts": "Pteris pectiniformis, the leaves of this plant are used in traditional medicine, particularly in East Asia, for their purported health benefits. The leaves are believed to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. In traditional Chinese medicine, Pteris pectiniformis is used to treat various health conditions, including fever, cough, and digestive issues. The plant's leaves are often used in herbal teas or infusions, and they can also be consumed raw or dried. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties and potential uses of Pteris pectiniformis.",
    "intro": "Pteris pectiniformis, also known as the fan fern or Chinese brake fern, is a species of fern that belongs to the family Pteridaceae. The plant has been used in traditional medicine for its various health benefits, including anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and anticoagulant properties, which may help to alleviate conditions such as arthritis, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease. The bioactive constituents of Pteris pectiniformis include flavonoids, alkaloids, and saponins, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional Chinese medicine, the plant is often prepared as a tea or infused in hot water to make a decoction, and it is also used in the production of tablets, capsules, and tinctures."
